Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Data Overview¶

  • Observations- The average age of depositors is ~45 years old, with the youngest customer being 23 years old and the oldest customer being 67 years old. The average number of years of experience amongst customers is ~20 years, with 75% of the customers having at least 10 years of experience, and 25% of the customers having at least 30 years of experience.

  • The average income amongst depositors is $73,774. This ranges from $8,000 to $224,000. 75% of customers made more than $39,000 annually, and 25% of customers made more than $98,000 annually. This indicates there may be some outliers to be found in the dataset for income

  • Certain zip codes are clearly over-represented in our dataset, and are currently incorrectly categorized as a numerical variable, we therefore need to convert the numerical columns that should be categorical types to type 'category'

  • Sanity checks- We observe certain columns need to be converted to type 'category'. We also observe there is a strong chance that we have outlier values within our experience, income, age, mortgage, and avg credit card spend per month group of variables.

  • I was initially unsure how to handle the zip codes and my initial hunch was to remove them because in a real-life scenario this information probably can't be used for decision making due to potential ethical challenges and regulatory dilemmas. However, to make better sense of the information presented from the zip codes I created a seperate dataframe composed of just the field/column names, and added seperate columns for the ratio of income/mortgage/CCAvg in a given zipcode vs that of the average dataset to produce a more standardized measure that can be used for outlier detection. The results demonstrate that most zipcodes that have incomes that are below, at, or near the 1-2x the mean income, with very few rows in the dataset containing incomes at more than 3x.

Exploratory Data Analysis.¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What is the distribution of mortgage attribute? Are there any noticeable patterns or outliers in the distribution?-
  • ~69.2% of the customers (OR 3,462 customers) in the dataset do not have a mortgage balance remaining. The remaining ~31% however do, with an average remaining balance of ~$56,498.80.
  1. How many customers have credit cards?
  • 3,530 customers or 70.6% of the customers in this dataset do not have a credit card issued by the bank. In contrast, 1,470 customers (29.4%) do have a credit card issued by the bank.
  1. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with the target attribute (personal loan)?
  • The attributes that have the strongest correlation with the target variable (Personal_Loan) are income(0.5), CCAvg (0.37), and CD_Account (0.32). Following these are Education (0.14) and Mortgage (0.14).
  1. How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their age?
  • Amongst the 18-24 year age bucket, no customers have accepted the loan offer. However, when moving up the age bucket- into the 25-34 year age bucket, ~10.9% of the customers accepted the offers. Amongst the middle of the age distribution (between 35 and 54), the acceptance rate was ~9.0%. The category that demonstrated the highest acceptance rate however was 55+ at ~12.1%.
  1. How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their education?

Bachelor Degrees- 93/ (93 + 182 + 205) = 93/480 ~19.4% Masters Degrees- 182/(93 + 182 + 205) = 182/480 ~37.9% Advanced/Professional- 205/(93+182+205) = 205/480 ~42.7%

~80% of all customers who accepted the previous loan offer had either a Masters Degree or were categorized as Advanced/Professional. Only ~20% had a Bachelors Degree.

Data Preprocessing¶

  • Analyzing the correlation heatmap a few things stand out- first, first we notice a strong correlation between Personal Loan acceptance and Income (0.50), and a strong correlation between Income and CCAvg as well (0.65), suggesting that Personal Loan acceptance should be driven by customers that have high incomes and high avg monthly spending on their credit cards (CCAvg).I also observed that there is a moderate correlation between Personal Loan Acceptance and CCAvg (0.37), and a relatively weak correlation between Income and Mortgage (0.21)- indicating those who have higher mortgage balances likely have higher incomes as well.

Missing value treatment- We did not spotlight any missing values, but we will need to figure out how to handle the zip codes correctly and encode them into our model. The biggest choice to consider is whether to drop zip code from our dataset before running the model, as it could be argued the column is primarily noise given that only ~20% of all zipcodes that significant relationships with other key explanatory variables, and thus the other ~80% might be adding significant noise.

  • We added feature engineering to the dataset in 2 ways:
  1. First- instead of dropping the zip codes, we are going to use them to build informative features that we can add to our model. From intuition, the goal is to encourage the model to select offer recipients that have higher incomes, higher Avg Credit Card spend, and lower mortgage balances, and we will create standardized ratios to measure this for each zipcode in our dataset. Next, we will need to see whether the original zipcodes and the newly created features are highly correlated if they are, we might need to consider dropping one of them- for regression this is crystal clear but for decision trees it is less so.
  • Outlier detection and treatment (if needed)- Since all the observations represent "real" observations and there are no outliers due to data entry, we will make no changes here.
  • Preparing data for modeling- Categorical features have already been encoded
  • Any other preprocessing steps (if needed) - Choose Approach for Model Building given Desired End Goal

# Ensure numerical columns are appropriately typed
df['Income'] = df['Income'].astype(float)
df['CCAvg'] = df['CCAvg'].astype(float)
df['Mortgage'] = df['Mortgage'].astype(float)

##Feature Engineering- Create standardized columns for income, mortgage, and credit card spend measuring the spread between zipcode income, CCAvg, and Mortgage to the overall average of the dataset for that variable##
df['ZipCode_Income_Ratio'] = df.groupby('ZIPCode')['Income'].transform(lambda x: x/x.mean())
df['ZipCode_CCAvg_Ratio'] = df.groupby('ZIPCode')['CCAvg'].transform(lambda x: x/x.mean())
df['ZipCode_Mortgage_Ratio'] = df.groupby('ZIPCode')['Mortgage'].transform(lambda x: x/x.mean())

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Model Evaluation Criteria:

  1. Balance between Recall and Precision (F1-Score)
  2. Maintain strong accuracy, recall, precision, and F-1 Scores greater than 0.9 on each criteria.
  3. Choose the model that provides the best balanced outcome on the TEST SET

In the first iteration, the decision tree overfit and model performance between the testing and training dataset diverged quite substantially. Even though the model test set fulfilled the criteria of greater than 99% accuracy, recall, and precision on non-loan customers, it performed noticeably worse on predicting the loan customers that would accept the loan even though in all metrics the test dataset still achieved greater than 90%+ on every metric. However, our initial criteria of having a model than neither favors nor dis-favors loan acceptances vs loan rejectors disproportionately has been fulfilled.

This model could be improved in 2 ways-

  1. Pre-pruning the decision tree by preventing it from growing to its full depth (thus not allowing it to overfit)
  2. Post-pruning where we build the decision tree then apply cost complexity pruning techniques to trim/remove branches that are not contributing to our predictive power.

  • Apply pre-pruning techniques substantially improved the generalizability of the model eliminating the gap between the training and test performance observed from the first overfit decision tree model. In fact, the test performance is actually stronger than the training performance.
  • In the context of this problem, the goal is to maximize the number of customers that accept the loan offerings and thus we want to maximize our recall score- which tells us the percentage of actual acceptances that the model correctly predicted. We observe the pre-pruned decision tree model has a ~97% recalll score and ~94% F-1 Score, and 91% precision. This indicates that we have optimized the model for recall but have done so at a slight cost to precision
  • This means ~9% of the time we will waste resources targeting customers that will not accept our loan acceptance. However our model identifies the customers that will accept our loan offerings ~97% of the time. This represents a highly acceptable tradeoff and maximizing recall is critical in this context where not identifying a customer is costlier than mis-identifying them leading to lost resources. Simply put, the cost of lost business and revenue $$ for a growing bank is greater than the cost we will incur through wasted marketing resources.
  • In practice, we want to achieve a balance of these two things. An F-Score of 94% indicates that we are achieving a good balance of these things.

##Final Step- we apply cost-complexity pruning to determine if there is a simplier model that might be easier to deploy and to validate the robustness of our existing approach##

##Calculate cost complexity parameters on our model##
post_pruned_model = decision_tree2.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)

##Parse out the components from above##
ccp_alphas, impurities = post_pruned_model.ccp_alphas, post_pruned_model.impurities

print("CCP Alphas:", ccp_alphas)

print("Impurities:", impurities)

##We now want to observe CCP Alphas against impurity for both the training and test datasets##
train_f1_scores=[]
test_f1_scores=[]

for alpha in ccp_alphas:
  model = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', splitter='best', max_depth=starting_max_depth, min_samples_split=30, ccp_alpha=alpha)
  model.fit(X_train, y_train)

  #Create training prediction##
  y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
  y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)

  #Calculate F1 scores##
  train_f1_scores.append(f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred))
  test_f1_scores.append(f1_score(y_test, y_test_pred))


##Plot the tradeoff between Alpha and Impurities in the training dataset##
plt.figure(figsize= (15,12));

#Plot training set#
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, train_f1_scores, marker='o', label='Training Set', drawstyle="steps-post")
#Plot test set#
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, test_f1_scores, marker='o', label='Test Set', drawstyle="steps-post")
plt.xlabel("Alpha")
plt.ylabel("F1 Score")
plt.title("F1 Score vs. Alpha for Training and Test Set")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

  • What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

  1. Customers that have an annual income greater than $90,000-$100,000 should be targeted for loan offers.

  2. Analyzing our feature importances, we observe that the variables Education, Income, and Family Size explained ~82% of the decisions our model made, which indicates these 3 variables are the most important variables in our recommendations.

  3. The model we built is optimized to successfully predict 97% of all loan customers, indicating it mis-categorizes just 3% of all loan customers as non-acceptors. In contrast, the model has a precision of ~91% indicating that 9% of all non-loan customers are expected to be incorrectly categorized as acceptors. The model was optimized for recall so that it minimizes the number of customer missed.

  4. Considering the cost of missing customers is likely significantly greater than the cost of wasted marketing resources, this is both an acceptable and an optimal tradeoff. F-1 Score for non-loan customers is ~99% and F-1 Score for loan customers is ~94%. Indicating a balanced tradeoff between false positives (leading to wasted marketing resources) and false negatives (leading to missed/lost customer opportunities).
